if that's not you,

00:38:31.100 --> 00:38:34.900 align:middle line:84%
then you know somebody and
love somebody who's struggling.

00:38:34.900 --> 00:38:37.460 align:middle line:84%
So therefore, everyone
in our society

00:38:37.460 --> 00:38:41.110 align:middle line:84%
is touched by this
massive problem.

00:38:41.110 --> 00:38:45.870 align:middle line:84%
And yet, 80 years after this
man had his spiritual awakening

00:38:45.870 --> 00:38:48.160 align:middle line:84%
and realized that all it
took was one person who

00:38:48.160 --> 00:38:52.110 align:middle line:84%
has the affliction of alcoholism
to help another person-- 80

00:38:52.110 --> 00:38:56.210 align:middle line:84%
years later, we're still
living in a society

00:38:56.210 --> 00:39:01.270 align:middle line:84%
where people feel the need
to be secretive, to be quiet.

00:39:01.270 --> 00:39:04.060 align:middle line:84%
We're still,
metaphorically speaking,

00:39:04.060 --> 00:39:05.900 align:middle line:90%
in the church basement.

00:39:05.900 --> 00:39:08.110 align:middle line:90%
12 step meetings are down there.

00:39:08.110 --> 00:39:10.450 align:middle line:84%
When is the conversation
going to come up

00:39:10.450 --> 00:39:13.110 align:middle line:90%
into the light of day?

00:39:13.110 --> 00:39:18.760 align:middle line:84%
We have a society that treats
addicts like they're criminals.

00:39:18.760 --> 00:39:21.710 align:middle line:84%
It doesn't understand that
addiction comes from trauma,

00:39:21.710 --> 00:39:27.200 align:middle line:84%
that we are criminalizing
traumatized people.

00:39:27.200 --> 00:39:28.770 align:middle line:84%
Our prison population
is the biggest

00:39:28.770 --> 00:39:30.880 align:middle line:90%
in the world per capita.

00:39:30.880 --> 00:39:33.600 align:middle line:84%
We take more drugs per
capita than any other country

00:39:33.600 --> 00:39:35.040 align:middle line:90%
in the world.

00:39:35.040 --> 00:39:39.760 align:middle line:84%
We spend more money on medical
problems related to alcoholism

00:39:39.760 --> 00:39:42.756 align:middle line:84%
and drug addiction than any
other country in the world.

00:39:42.756 --> 00:39:43.431 align:middle line:90%
[END PLAYBACK]

00:39:43.431 --> 00:39:45.430 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: You set out a
very important point there

00:39:45.430 --> 00:39:49.770 align:middle line:84%
about that we are criminalizing
traumatized people.

00:39:49.770 --> 00:39:51.560 align:middle line:84%
Most of the people
in prison have

00:39:51.560 --> 00:39:56.344 align:middle line:84%
had some type of deep trauma in
their past, like 99% of them,

00:39:56.344 --> 00:39:58.500 align:middle line:90%
or a very, very high percent.

00:39:58.500 --> 00:40:04.150 align:middle line:84%
So what can we do
instead of putting

00:40:04.150 --> 00:40:07.580 align:middle line:84%
people who have had deep,
unresolved trauma in prison?

00:40:07.580 --> 00:40:10.910 align:middle line:84%
>>ROSEN: Well, this
is just a huge point.

00:40:10.910 --> 00:40:11.530 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Huge.

00:40:11.530 --> 00:40:14.560 align:middle line:84%
>>ROSEN: We have the
largest prison population

00:40:14.560 --> 00:40:16.950 align:middle line:84%
in the world in
the United States.

00:40:16.950 --> 00:40:19.850 align:middle line:84%
So if you took the entire
prison population of the world,

00:40:19.850 --> 00:40:22.750 align:middle line:84%
the United States
represents 25% of it.

00:40:22.750 --> 00:40:23.310 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Wow.

00:40:23.310 --> 00:40:25.670 align:middle line:84%
>>ROSEN: So that means that
one in four people in prison

00:40:25.670 --> 00:40:28.020 align:middle line:84%
in the world happen to be
from the land of the free.

00:40:28.020 --> 00:40:29.800 align:middle line:90%


00:40:29.800 --> 00:40:31.800 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: That's an interesting
way of putting it.

00:40:31.800 --> 00:40:34.340 align:middle line:84%
>>ROSEN: There's an
unfortunate irony there.

00:40:34.340 --> 00:40:35.890 align:middle line:84%
But the people
that are in prison

00:40:35.890 --> 00:40:39.550 align:middle line:84%
are-- the non-violent
offenders, so many of them

00:40:39.550 --> 00:40:43.110 align:middle line:84%
are people who struggle
with addiction, alcoholism.

00:40:43.110 --> 00:40:45.800 align:middle line:84%
In particular, I'll just
say one more statistic.

00:40:45.800 --> 00:40:49.880 align:middle line:84%
Alcohol is related in
40% of violent crime.

00:40:49.880 --> 00:40:52.930 align:middle line:84%
Alcohol has a part in
40% of violent crime.

00:40:52.930 --> 00:40:57.960 align:middle line:84%
But if we're going to
talk about how to change,

00:40:57.960 --> 00:41:01.420 align:middle line:84%
how to treat people
who are traumatized,

00:41:01.420 --> 00:41:05.250 align:middle line:84%
certainly we can't treat them
by traumatizing them further.

00:41:05.250 --> 00:41:09.980 align:middle line:84%
That wouldn't be a
protocol that would

00:41:09.980 --> 00:41:12.280 align:middle line:90%
help them or help society.

00:41:12.280 --> 00:41:15.300 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So the addiction--
I mean, the trauma

00:41:15.300 --> 00:41:17.110 align:middle line:84%
sets off the
addiction that leads

00:41:17.110 --> 00:41:19.380 align:middle line:84%
to the alcohol or the
drug abuse that then leads

00:41:19.380 --> 00:41:21.130 align:middle line:84%
to the criminal
act, that then goes

00:41:21.130 --> 00:41:24.910 align:middle line:84%
right back into the system
of more trauma in the prison

00:41:24.910 --> 00:41:25.710 align:middle line:90%
system, right?

00:41:25.710 --> 00:41:26.400 align:middle line:90%
>>ROSEN: Yes.

00:41:26.400 --> 00:41:28.945 align:middle line:84%
One of my mentors and
someone I really admire a lot

00:41:28.945 --> 00:41:31.020 align:middle line:90%
is Dr. Gabor Mate.

00:41:31.020 --> 00:41:33.000 align:middle line:84%
He writes a lot about
addiction and speaks--

00:41:33.000 --> 00:41:36.060 align:middle line:84%
he's an exceptional
speaker and presenter.

00:41:36.060 --> 00:41:39.330 align:middle line:84%
He talks a lot about this
idea of all addiction coming

00:41:39.330 --> 00:41:42.900 align:middle line:84%
from trauma, all addiction
coming from trauma.

00:41:42.900 --> 00:41:46.400 align:middle line:84%
And so if you take a
traumatized person and you're

00:41:46.400 --> 00:41:48.780 align:middle line:84%
going to chase them and
persecute them and put them

00:41:48.780 --> 00:41:51.470 align:middle line:84%
behind bars with a bunch of
other traumatized people, some

00:41:51.470 --> 00:41:54.010 align:middle line:84%
of whom are very
violent, we know

00:41:54.010 --> 00:41:56.600 align:middle line:84%
this is not leading in
the correct direction.

00:41:56.600 --> 00:41:59.260 align:middle line:84%
So if you're going
to take-- if you

00:41:59.260 --> 00:42:02.150 align:middle line:84%
want to punish a
traumatized person,

00:42:02.150 --> 00:42:05.410 align:middle line:84%
you first ask
yourself, in so doing,

00:42:05.410 --> 00:42:08.870 align:middle line:84%
is that going to be for
the betterment of society?

00:42:08.870 --> 00:42:11.410 align:middle line:84%
Is that going to be for the
common good of everybody?

00:42:11.410 --> 00:42:12.030 align:middle line:90%
Of course not.

00:42:12.030 --> 00:42:14.314 align:middle line:84%
It's not for the
common good of anybody.

00:42:14.314 --> 00:42:16.355 align:middle line:84%
So we have to get out of
the punishment mentality

00:42:16.355 --> 00:42:17.730 align:middle line:90%
and realize, OK.

00:42:17.730 --> 00:42:19.582 align:middle line:90%
This is a sick person.

00:42:19.582 --> 00:42:21.040 align:middle line:84%
This is a person
who's traumatized.

00:42:21.040 --> 00:42:22.470 align:middle line:90%
So how do we treat them?

00:42:22.470 --> 00:42:24.779 align:middle line:84%
Well, we treat them
with treatment.

00:42:24.779 --> 00:42:25.820 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: That makes sense.

00:42:25.820 --> 00:42:29.350 align:middle line:84%
>>ROSEN: So there's primary
treatment for addiction.

00:42:29.350 --> 00:42:33.850 align:middle line:84%
There's all manner of
trauma-related modalities

00:42:33.850 --> 00:42:36.490 align:middle line:90%
of recovering from trauma.

00:42:36.490 --> 00:42:39.860 align:middle line:84%
There's so much we're
learning about PTSD right now

00:42:39.860 --> 00:42:41.370 align:middle line:84%
with our military,
but also people

00:42:41.370 --> 00:42:44.950 align:middle line:84%
who have come out of really
rough childhoods have PTSD.

00:42:44.950 --> 00:42:48.490 align:middle line:84%
We actually know a lot about
treating that condition.

00:42:48.490 --> 00:42:50.580 align:middle line:84%
Half of these
people are dyslexic.

00:42:50.580 --> 00:42:53.600 align:middle line:90%
You've got conditions like ADD.

00:42:53.600 --> 00:42:58.230 align:middle line:84%
You have a population of people
who feel like they're separate,

00:42:58.230 --> 00:43:01.410 align:middle line:84%
who feel like they're alone,
who don't feel supported,

00:43:01.410 --> 00:43:04.520 align:middle line:84%
who feel like they're not
going to have their needs met

00:43:04.520 --> 00:43:07.030 align:middle line:84%
in the world, so they have
to go out and take it.

00:43:07.030 --> 00:43:08.410 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes, or numb it.

00:43:08.410 --> 00:43:09.650 align:middle line:90%
>>ROSEN: Or numb it.

00:43:09.650 --> 00:43:12.400 align:middle line:84%
And so what we have
to do is we have to--

00:43:12.400 --> 00:43:16.729 align:middle line:84%
in the most plain terms, we have
to connect with these people.

00:43:16.729 --> 00:43:18.770 align:middle line:84%
We have to not treat them
like they're less than.

00:43:18.770 --> 00:43:20.940 align:middle line:84%
We have to treat them
like they need something,

00:43:20.940 --> 00:43:22.930 align:middle line:84%
and to help work
with them to get them

00:43:22.930 --> 00:43:26.690 align:middle line:84%
what they need so that they can
become a healthier individual.

00:43:26.690 --> 00:43:29.660 align:middle line:84%
And ultimately, a productive
member of society.

00:43:29.660 --> 00:43:34.370 align:middle line:84%
And ultimately, a content
and vibrant human being.

00:43:34.370 --> 00:43:37.350 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So do you think that
12 step programs, treatment

00:43:37.350 --> 00:43:42.700 align:middle line:84%
centers, recovery centers, and
yoga are the way to do that?

00:43:42.700 --> 00:43:44.760 align:middle line:90%
>>ROSEN: Absolutely.

00:43:44.760 --> 00:43:47.970 align:middle line:84%
Certainly a better step, a
better place to go for sure.

00:43:47.970 --> 00:43:50.080 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: What's the ultimate?

00:43:50.080 --> 00:43:53.700 align:middle line:84%
>>ROSEN: Well, the ultimate
is to have a program that's

00:43:53.700 --> 00:43:58.010 align:middle line:84%
based upon love,
kindness, compassion,

00:43:58.010 --> 00:44:00.930 align:middle line:84%
that brings together
modalities of healing

00:44:00.930 --> 00:44:03.430 align:middle line:90%
such as yoga, meditation.

00:44:03.430 --> 00:44:05.610 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So ashrams
would be the new prison.

00:44:05.610 --> 00:44:07.530 align:middle line:84%
>>ROSEN: I think so,
without question.

00:44:07.530 --> 00:44:08.140 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Wow.

00:44:08.140 --> 00:44:11.006 align:middle line:84%
>>ROSEN: If you could create
a community of people that--

00:44:11.006 --> 00:44:12.380 align:middle line:84%
now understand,
we're not talking

00:44:12.380 --> 00:44:16.290 align:middle line:84%
about violent,
pathological criminals.

00:44:16.290 --> 00:44:19.080 align:middle line:84%
They're not going to fit
within this particular view.

00:44:19.080 --> 00:44:20.900 align:middle line:84%
There's different
problems there that

00:44:20.900 --> 00:44:24.020 align:middle line:84%
need to be treated
in some kind of way.

00:44:24.020 --> 00:44:28.030 align:middle line:84%
You couldn't find a male
in the United States

00:44:28.030 --> 00:44:29.950 align:middle line:84%
that hasn't at
some point thought

00:44:29.950 --> 00:44:33.930 align:middle line:84%
of the horror of
being raped in prison.

00:44:33.930 --> 00:44:39.280 align:middle line:84%
And I'm talking about-- I'm
not too close to prison,

00:44:39.280 --> 00:44:42.560 align:middle line:84%
but there's many times in my
past I could have gone there.

00:44:42.560 --> 00:44:45.290 align:middle line:84%
But for some reason, and
I thank god every day,

00:44:45.290 --> 00:44:46.831 align:middle line:90%
I didn't have to go there.

00:44:46.831 --> 00:44:48.330 align:middle line:84%
But there's no one
alive today who's

00:44:48.330 --> 00:44:50.320 align:middle line:84%
my age who doesn't
think about that.

00:44:50.320 --> 00:44:51.990 align:middle line:84%
We've seen too
many images on TV.

00:44:51.990 --> 00:44:54.480 align:middle line:84%
We've seen-- we've
heard the stories.

00:44:54.480 --> 00:44:58.220 align:middle line:84%
This is what our solution is
for people who are criminals?

00:44:58.220 --> 00:45:01.390 align:middle line:84%
We're going to put them into a--
basically a hotbed of addiction

00:45:01.390 --> 00:45:03.180 align:middle line:90%
with other criminals?

00:45:03.180 --> 00:45:06.560 align:middle line:84%
How can that be the solution
of a merciful society?

00:45:06.560 --> 00:45:09.860 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Well, in
the case of recovery

00:45:09.860 --> 00:45:12.270 align:middle line:84%
and where you're talking
about acute drug abuse

00:45:12.270 --> 00:45:15.930 align:middle line:84%
here, when somebody
goes into a place,

00:45:15.930 --> 00:45:19.070 align:middle line:84%
and to avoid all of that, and
avoid going into a prison,

00:45:19.070 --> 00:45:22.550 align:middle line:84%
someone needs to stay in a place
of their right mind, right?

00:45:22.550 --> 00:45:25.810 align:middle line:84%
So they need to stay
in a place of recovery.

00:45:25.810 --> 00:45:26.930 align:middle line:90%
>>ROSEN: For a while.

00:45:26.930 --> 00:45:27.715 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Forever.

00:45:27.715 --> 00:45:30.150 align:middle line:84%
>>ROSEN: Or they have to
stay on the path of recovery,

00:45:30.150 --> 00:45:32.100 align:middle line:84%
sure, one day at
a time, forever.

00:45:32.100 --> 00:45:33.100 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Oh, OK.

00:45:33.100 --> 00:45:34.710 align:middle line:84%
And how do you
suggest someone can

00:45:34.710 --> 00:45:36.740 align:middle line:84%
do that to avoid all
that we just talked about

00:45:36.740 --> 00:45:37.730 align:middle line:90%
with the prisons?

00:45:37.730 --> 00:45:41.760 align:middle line:84%
How do you avoid that and stay
on that one day at a time?

00:45:41.760 --> 00:45:42.810 align:middle line:90%
How do you stay there?

00:45:42.810 --> 00:45:44.393 align:middle line:84%
>>ROSEN: Are you
asking me, or are you

00:45:44.393 --> 00:45:47.700 align:middle line:84%
asking a person who
struggles with crime?

00:45:47.700 --> 00:45:48.270 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Hm.

00:45:48.270 --> 00:45:50.490 align:middle line:90%
I'm asking everyone.

00:45:50.490 --> 00:45:54.200 align:middle line:84%
>>ROSEN: Well, the way--
if you're asking me,

00:45:54.200 --> 00:45:58.090 align:middle line:84%
what I teach in the
world is, in my opinion,

00:45:58.090 --> 00:46:02.150 align:middle line:84%
one of the greatest,
most powerful, spiritual,

00:46:02.150 --> 00:46:06.570 align:middle line:84%
and logistically correct
approaches to life

00:46:06.570 --> 00:46:09.430 align:middle line:84%
is the one day at
a time philosophy.

00:46:09.430 --> 00:46:12.370 align:middle line:84%
Start to bring it
down into a day.

00:46:12.370 --> 00:46:14.240 align:middle line:84%
If you're in the
beginning of your recovery

00:46:14.240 --> 00:46:16.210 align:middle line:84%
and you're craving
drugs and alcohol,

00:46:16.210 --> 00:46:19.200 align:middle line:84%
you're craving whatever it is
that's your drug of choice,

00:46:19.200 --> 00:46:21.450 align:middle line:84%
and you don't know how you're
going to get through it,

00:46:21.450 --> 00:46:24.320 align:middle line:84%
and will this ever
pass, all you need to do

00:46:24.320 --> 00:46:27.820 align:middle line:90%
is get to bed without using.

00:46:27.820 --> 00:46:33.410 align:middle line:84%
Just go to sleep at night
not having used that day.

00:46:33.410 --> 00:46:35.910 align:middle line:90%
And that's a successful day.

00:46:35.910 --> 00:46:38.170 align:middle line:84%
Later on, one day at
a time takes much more

00:46:38.170 --> 00:46:39.490 align:middle line:90%
of a spiritual significance.

00:46:39.490 --> 00:46:40.214 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Right.

00:46:40.214 --> 00:46:42.380 align:middle line:84%
Because you're not going
to do it by just saying no.

00:46:42.380 --> 00:46:44.640 align:middle line:84%
You have to have a
practice within the waking

00:46:44.640 --> 00:46:45.600 align:middle line:90%
hours of that day.

00:46:45.600 --> 00:46:46.570 align:middle line:90%
>>ROSEN: That's right.

00:46:46.570 --> 00:46:49.170 align:middle line:84%
And you start to realize
that nothing is ever

00:46:49.170 --> 00:46:51.050 align:middle line:90%
going to happen tomorrow.

00:46:51.050 --> 00:46:53.100 align:middle line:90%
I have today, only today.

00:46:53.100 --> 00:46:58.510 align:middle line:84%
I'm developing a relationship
with presence, with the now.

00:46:58.510 --> 00:47:00.510 align:middle line:84%
Eckhart Tolle obviously
writes a lot about this.

00:47:00.510 --> 00:47:03.980 align:middle line:84%
We are going to create a
relationship with ourself which

00:47:03.980 --> 00:47:06.360 align:middle line:84%
can be comfortable
in the here and now.

00:47:06.360 --> 00:47:08.260 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: OK, yes.

00:47:08.260 --> 00:47:10.090 align:middle line:84%
>>ROSEN: The creation
of that ability

00:47:10.090 --> 00:47:15.150 align:middle line:84%
to sit still, to cultivate a
relationship with oneself is,

00:47:15.150 --> 00:47:19.940 align:middle line:84%
to me, the antidote to addiction
and the antidote to crime.

00:47:19.940 --> 00:47:21.950 align:middle line:84%
But lately, as
far as I can tell,

00:47:21.950 --> 00:47:24.710 align:middle line:84%
we haven't really been
teaching that in prison much.

00:47:24.710 --> 00:47:27.559 align:middle line:84%
There's a few programs that we
hear about now and then, but--

00:47:27.559 --> 00:47:30.100 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Programs that come into
the prisons, but not programs

00:47:30.100 --> 00:47:32.110 align:middle line:84%
you can go to instead
of the prisons.

00:47:32.110 --> 00:47:33.640 align:middle line:84%
>>ROSEN: Well
absolutely, and look,

00:47:33.640 --> 00:47:37.079 align:middle line:84%
if you put any human
being on crack cocaine,

00:47:37.079 --> 00:47:38.620 align:middle line:84%
or you put any human
being on heroin,

00:47:38.620 --> 00:47:43.320 align:middle line:84%
you bring into them the
phenomenon of craving.

00:47:43.320 --> 00:47:47.036 align:middle line:84%
I'm telling you, that that
person, whoever they were--

00:47:47.036 --> 00:47:49.535 align:middle line:84%
I don't care what their moral
standing is, I don't care what

00:47:49.535 --> 00:47:51.584 align:middle line:84%
their ethics are--
they will steal.

00:47:51.584 --> 00:47:52.250 align:middle line:90%
They will cheat.

00:47:52.250 --> 00:47:55.500 align:middle line:84%
They will lie, and ultimately
they will kill if they have to.

00:47:55.500 --> 00:47:56.876 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: To get
back to that drug.

00:47:56.876 --> 00:47:58.250 align:middle line:84%
>>ROSEN: It's not
because they're

00:47:58.250 --> 00:48:00.042 align:middle line:84%
a cheater, a liar, a
thief, and a murderer.

00:48:00.042 --> 00:48:01.666 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: It's because
they're an addict.

00:48:01.666 --> 00:48:03.400 align:middle line:84%
>>ROSEN: It's because
they're an addict.

00:48:03.400 --> 00:48:05.150 align:middle line:90%
And that's how addicts behave.

00:48:05.150 --> 00:48:08.560 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Well, there is a great
clip here of you talking about

00:48:08.560 --> 00:48:11.240 align:middle line:84%
is it true that once an
addict, always an addict?

00:48:11.240 --> 00:48:12.094 align:middle line:90%
Take a look.

